<h2>Job Description</h2>

<p>Your primary job function is to develop cutting-edge Ruby on Rails
web applications to meet the changing needs of our clients. Therefore, a
good grasp of object oriented programming (particularly the
Model-View-Controller pattern), a bit of database design, and a very
strong command of HTML/CSS/JS will be needed to hit the ground running.
In addition to these core skills, here are a few more of the things you
will be using regularly:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Subversion</li>
  <li>Mac OS X</li>
  <li>MySQL</li>
  <li>Photoshop</li>
  <li>XML, XSL, XSL-FO</li>
  <li>Flash/Flex/ActionScript</li>
  <li>XML and REST web services</li>
  <li>Apache</li>
  <li>Linux (Fedora/Centos)</li>
</ul>

<p>If you haven't heard of any of these, you may be in trouble. If you
have heard of them but are not already proficient in these skills, you
must be confident that you can pick them up quickly. Ideally, just
looking through the list motivated you to get up and learn
something.</p>

<p>Related experience is helpful, but not necessary. We have a variety
of projects to work on, from brain-dead simple to dizzyingly complex, so
we will start you at an appropriate level and go from there.</p>

<p>Keep in mind that being full-timer #3 means that you will be an
integral part of the company. At times, this will be less than
glamorous. Sometimes this will involve making copies and checking our
mailbox. Sometimes, this will involve working directly with clients. And
it will almost certainly involve high-fives and drinks when we close a
big deal. But even though you will be "the new guy," we won't unload on
you all the tasks we hate. You will see us performing a range of tasks,
big and small.</p>


